SQS Queue Monitoring & Alerting – QA Implementation (EKS)
🔹 1. Overview

This implementation provides proactive monitoring and alerting for Amazon SQS queues used by EKS-based consumer services.

Goal: Detect issues early such as:

Backlog buildup (consumers not keeping up)
Message processing delays (stuck or slow processing)
Abnormal in-flight message behavior

End-to-end flow:

SQS → CloudWatch Metrics → CloudWatch Alarms → SNS → Lambda → Moogsoft (QA)

When thresholds are breached, alerts are sent to Moogsoft (QA) for centralized incident visibility.

🔹 2. Architecture (Explained)
Producer → SQS Queue → EKS Consumer Pods
                     ↓
               CloudWatch Metrics
                     ↓
               CloudWatch Alarms
                     ↓
                    SNS
                     ↓
                  Lambda
                     ↓
              Moogsoft (QA)
How each component works:
SQS Queue
Stores messages produced by upstream systems.
EKS pods consume these messages.
CloudWatch Metrics
AWS automatically publishes SQS metrics every minute.
CloudWatch Alarms
Evaluates metrics against thresholds.
Changes state: OK → ALARM → OK.
SNS (Simple Notification Service)
Acts as a messaging layer.
Sends alarm events to subscribers (Lambda, email).
Lambda
Transforms CloudWatch alarm payload into Moogsoft format.
Sends HTTP POST request to Moogsoft API.
Moogsoft (QA)
Receives alerts and creates incidents/events.
🔹 3. Monitored SQS Metrics (Deep Explanation)
1️⃣ ApproximateNumberOfMessagesVisible
Meaning: Messages available for consumption.
Interpretation:
0 → No backlog
Increasing → Consumers lagging
Why important: Primary indicator of backlog
2️⃣ ApproximateNumberOfMessagesNotVisible
Meaning: Messages currently being processed (in-flight)
Interpretation:
High value → Active processing
Stuck high → Consumers may be hanging
Why important: Detect processing issues
3️⃣ ApproximateAgeOfOldestMessage
Meaning: Time (seconds) since oldest message entered queue
Interpretation:
Low → Healthy processing
High → Messages stuck / slow processing
Why important: Detect latency and SLA violations
🔹 4. CloudWatch Alarm Configuration (Detailed)
General Settings
Namespace: AWS/SQS
Period: 1 minute
Statistic: Average
Evaluation Frequency: Every 1 minute
🔸 Alarm 1: Queue Backlog (sqs_visible)
Metric: ApproximateNumberOfMessagesVisible
Condition: > 5
Purpose: Detect when messages accumulate faster than consumption

Behavior:

0–5 messages → OK

5 messages → ALARM

🔸 Alarm 2: Oldest Message Age (sqs_old_msg)
Metric: ApproximateAgeOfOldestMessage
Example Threshold: > 60 seconds (QA)
Purpose: Detect delayed processing

Behavior:

Low age → OK
Increasing age → ALARM
🔸 Alarm 3: In-flight Messages (sqs_not_visible)
Metric: ApproximateNumberOfMessagesNotVisible
Purpose: Monitor processing load

Behavior:

Normal processing → OK
Sudden spike → ALARM (if configured)
🔹 5. Alarm Notification Flow (Step-by-Step)
Step 1: Alarm State Change

CloudWatch detects threshold breach:

OK → ALARM
Step 2: SNS Trigger
Alarm sends notification to SNS Topic
SNS acts as a fan-out mechanism
Step 3: Lambda Execution
SNS invokes Lambda
Lambda receives CloudWatch payload
Extracts:
Alarm name
Metric
State (ALARM / OK)
Timestamp
Step 4: Moogsoft API Call

Lambda sends HTTP POST request to:

https://moog-dev-appl-lb1.1dc.com/generic_rest
🔹 6. Moogsoft Payload (Explained)

Example:

{
  "source": "sqs-alerting-poc-queue",
  "source_id": "aws-sqs",
  "description": "SQS backlog threshold exceeded",
  "agent": "CloudWatch",
  "agent_location": "us-east-2",
  "class": "SQS",
  "type": "QueueBacklog",
  "severity": 5
}
Field Explanation
Field	Description
source	Queue name
source_id	Identifier of AWS service
description	Alert message
agent	Monitoring system (CloudWatch)
agent_location	AWS region
class	Resource type
type	Alert type
severity	Alert severity
Severity Mapping
CloudWatch State	Moogsoft Severity
ALARM	5 (Critical)
OK	0 (Clear)
